{{math-stub}}

In mathematics, the '''Taniyama group''' is a [[Group (mathematics)|group]] that is an [[Group extension|extension]] of the [[absolute Galois group]] of the [[Rational number|rationals]] by the [[Serre group]]. It was introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Langlands|authorlink=Robert Langlands|year=1977}} using an observation by [[Deligne]], and named after [[Yutaka Taniyama]]. It was intended to be the [[group scheme]] whose representations correspond to the (hypothetical) [[Complex multiplication|CM]] [[Motive (algebraic geometry)|motives]] over the field '''Q''' of rational numbers.
